# .dockerignore — Tells Docker which files to SKIP when doing "COPY . ."
#
# WHY THIS MATTERS:
# When you run "docker build", Docker sends ALL files in your project
# to the Docker daemon as "build context". Without .dockerignore:
#   - node_modules/ (50MB+) gets sent, even though we re-install in the Dockerfile
#   - .git/ history gets sent (could be huge)
#   - Test files get copied into the production image (unnecessary bloat)
#
# This is like .gitignore, but for Docker builds.

# Dependencies — we install fresh in the Dockerfile with "npm ci".
# Sending your local node_modules would waste time and could introduce
# platform-specific binaries (your Mac's modules won't work in Linux containers).
node_modules/

# Git history — not needed in the container
.git/
.gitignore

# GitHub Actions workflows — only needed by GitHub, not by the container
.github/

# Test files — we don't run tests inside the production container
*.test.js

# Environment files — may contain secrets, never bake into an image!
.env
.env.*

# IDE and OS files
.vscode/
.idea/
.DS_Store

# Documentation — not needed in the container
README.md
*.md

# Docker files — prevent recursive copying
Dockerfile
docker-compose*.yml
